I’ve added a dedicated section plus security framing woven throughout, so the CISO can point to it clearly.

Identity Strategy — Business Narrative (Security-Enhanced)
Why this matters now
At Macquarie, identity controls exist across the organisation, but they are complex, fragmented, and operationally heavy.
This creates risk in subtle but real ways:
	• Controls depend on manual steps
	• Access and authentication decisions are delayed or incomplete
	• Failures are detected late
	• Privileged access relies heavily on long-lived credentials
This strategy addresses these risks by design, while improving speed and reducing cost.

What we are changing
We are shifting identity from a control-by-process model to a control-by-design model.
Instead of relying on:
	• Human intervention
	• Periodic reviews
	• Static credentials
	• After-the-fact detection
We are building:
	• Real-time visibility
	• Automated enforcement
	• Short-lived trust
	• Continuous validation
This strengthens security while reducing operational effort.

How the strategy improves security posture
1. Controls move from periodic to continuous
What changes
	• Identity events are captured as they happen
	• Access, authentication, and privilege changes are observable in real time
	• Failures and anomalies are detected immediately
Security impact
	• Reduced window of exposure
	• Faster detection of misuse or misconfiguration
	• Better alignment with how applications and workloads actually operate

2. Privileged access shifts away from shared secrets
What changes
	• Fewer long-lived credentials
	• Reduced reliance on shared or generic accounts
	• Increased use of workload identity and attestation
Security impact
	• Lower risk of credential leakage
	• Reduced blast radius if a system is compromised
	• Stronger control over who or what can act with privilege
This materially improves Macquarie’s privilege risk profile.

3. Onboarding enforces security from day one
What changes
	• Applications are onboarded with access, authentication, and governance together
	• Security controls are not bolted on later
	• Identity standards are applied consistently
Security impact
	• Fewer gaps during early application lifecycle
	• Reduced risk of unmanaged access
	• Stronger baseline controls across the estate

4. Fewer manual controls means fewer human errors
What changes
	• Automation replaces repetitive manual steps
	• Identity decisions are made using structured data
	• Workflows are consistent and repeatable
Security impact
	• Reduced misconfigurations
	• Fewer missed revocations
	• Lower dependency on individual knowledge

5. Observability and SRE reduce operational risk
What changes
	• Identity platforms are monitored like critical services
	• Failures are visible and actionable
	• Recovery is faster and more predictable
Security impact
	• Reduced likelihood of prolonged control failures
	• Faster containment of issues
	• Increased confidence in automated enforcement

Security posture outcomes
By executing this strategy, Macquarie achieves:
	• Stronger preventive controls
	• Faster detection and response
	• Reduced privilege risk
	• Lower likelihood of audit findings
	• Improved resilience of identity services
Importantly, these improvements are structural, not dependent on increased process or headcount.

How this also reduces cost
Security improves because we remove complexity:
	• Fewer bespoke controls to manage
	• Less remediation work after failures
	• Lower audit and compliance effort
	• Reduced operational overhead in PAM and access management
Security and efficiency improve together.

Executive summary for CISO
	“This strategy strengthens Macquarie’s security posture by making identity controls continuous, automated, and observable — reducing privilege risk and operational exposure while lowering cost.”

One-line close for business leaders
	“We are reducing risk by simplifying identity — not by adding more process.”

