Perfect additions. I’ve woven both points in cleanly and business-first, without dragging the reader into technical depth. This version keeps the story intact, strengthens the security posture narrative, and makes it very clear you are modernising PAM and onboarding, not just tweaking tools.
Below is the revised business-facing narrative, with only the new concepts added and integrated naturally.

Identity Strategy — Business Narrative (Updated)
Why this matters now
At Macquarie, identity controls exist across the organisation, but they are hard to use, slow to change, and expensive to operate.
Business teams experience this as:
	• Long onboarding cycles
	• Repeated handoffs across teams
	• Manual reviews that don’t reflect reality
	• Limited visibility into who has access and why
	• Delays when authentication or access changes are required
This identity strategy is about fixing that experience, while strengthening control and reducing cost.

What we are changing
We are shifting identity from a tool-centric, ticket-driven model to a platform-based capability that manages:
	• Who can access systems
	• How systems authenticate
	• How workloads trust each other
	• How access is monitored and revoked
Instead of identity being:
	• Batch-based
	• Secrets-heavy
	• Manually operated
We are making identity:
	• Event-driven
	• Workload-aware
	• API-enabled
	• Observable and resilient

How we are actioning the strategy
1. Making identity data available in real time
What we are doing
	• Creating a real-time Identity Data Platform
	• Publishing identity lifecycle events, access changes, authentication outcomes, and privilege usage
	• Providing analytics and APIs for consumers
What this means for the business
	• No more spreadsheets or ad-hoc reporting
	• Real-time visibility into access, authentication, and privilege state
	• Faster investigation and decision-making
	• Identity data becomes actionable, not static

2. Simplifying onboarding — beyond access alone
What we are doing
	• Redesigning onboarding as an end-to-end identity process
	• Automating not just access provisioning, but:
		○ Authentication onboarding
		○ Role and entitlement setup
		○ Privileged access tagging
		○ Governance readiness
	• Using reusable workflows rather than bespoke steps per application
What this means for the business
	• Onboarding is faster and more predictable
	• Applications are ready for authentication, access, and governance from day one
	• Fewer manual steps and fewer handoffs
	• Less rework later when controls need to be enforced
Onboarding becomes a single, consistent process, not a series of disconnected tasks.

3. Moving PAM away from secrets to workload identity
What we are doing
	• Reducing reliance on long-lived secrets and shared credentials
	• Introducing machine and workload identity attestation
	• Allowing systems to authenticate based on who they are, not what secret they hold
	• Aligning PAM with modern workload communication patterns
What this means for the business
	• Fewer secrets to manage, rotate, and audit
	• Reduced operational risk from leaked or stale credentials
	• Faster onboarding of system-to-system integrations
	• Stronger control over privileged access without slowing delivery
PAM shifts from manual secret handling to automated trust between workloads.

4. Enabling self-service through one identity platform
What we are doing
	• Creating a single identity interaction layer
	• Power that layer using consistent APIs
	• Support multiple channels from the same foundation:
		○ UI
		○ System integrations
		○ Automation pipelines
What this means for the business
	• One way to interact with identity
	• Consistent behaviour across all channels
	• Less dependency on tickets and central teams
	• Identity becomes easier to adopt and easier to scale

5. Improving resilience and reliability
What we are doing
	• Introducing monitoring and observability across identity workflows
	• Tracking failures in access, authentication, and privilege processes
	• Applying SRE practices to identity platforms
What this means for the business
	• Fewer disruptions caused by identity failures
	• Faster recovery when issues occur
	• Confidence to automate more without increasing risk
	• Identity becomes predictable and dependable

How this reduces cost for the business
This strategy reduces cost by:
	• Removing 70–80% of manual access and privilege work
	• Reducing effort spent managing secrets and shared credentials
	• Eliminating duplicate onboarding and review processes
	• Lowering the cost of audits and remediation
	• Reducing reliance on specialist tooling and skills
The result is lower cost per application, lower cost per access change, and lower cost to operate identity controls.

How this improves quality
	• Access and authentication decisions are based on real-time data
	• Privileged access is short-lived and workload-bound
	• Reviews are accurate, targeted, and meaningful
	• Orphaned access and stale secrets are reduced
This leads to stronger controls, better audit outcomes, and lower operational risk.

How this accelerates delivery
	• Applications onboard faster and more consistently
	• Authentication and access are ready together
	• System integrations no longer depend on shared secrets
	• Identity becomes part of delivery pipelines, not a bottleneck
The business can move faster without weakening controls.

The outcome
By executing this identity strategy, we:
	• Reduce cost
	• Improve control quality
	• Increase delivery speed
	• Strengthen security posture
	• Create a better experience for business teams
Most importantly, identity becomes an enabler of business outcomes, not a constraint.

Executive one-liner
	“This strategy modernises identity across access, authentication, and privilege, reducing cost while making secure delivery faster and more reliable.”

