Below is a business-facing narrative, written deliberately in plain language, focused on outcomes, actions, and confidence, not identity jargon.
This is the version a CISO can confidently use with a Business Head to explain what is changing, what we are doing differently, and how it helps them.

Identity Strategy — Business Narrative
Why this matters now
At Macquarie, identity controls exist across the organisation, but they are hard to use, slow to change, and expensive to operate.
Business teams experience this as:
	• Long onboarding cycles
	• Repeated handoffs across teams
	• Manual reviews that don’t reflect reality
	• Limited visibility into who has access and why
	• Delays when changes are required
This identity strategy is about fixing that experience, while strengthening control and reducing cost.

What we are changing
We are shifting identity from a back-office function to a business-enabled platform.
Instead of identity being:
	• Ticket-driven
	• Batch-based
	• Tool-centric
We are making identity:
	• Data-driven
	• Event-based
	• API-enabled
	• Observable and resilient
This allows identity to support the business at speed, without increasing risk.

How we are actioning the strategy
1. Making identity data available in real time
What we are doing
	• Creating a real-time Identity Data Platform
	• Publishing identity events, access changes, and lifecycle outcomes as data
	• Providing analytics and APIs for consumers
What this means for the business
	• No more spreadsheets for entitlement data
	• No waiting for reports or dashboards to be built
	• Teams can see access posture, changes, and risks when they need it
	• Identity data becomes usable, not locked inside systems

2. Simplifying onboarding and access changes
What we are doing
	• Building reusable onboarding and lifecycle workflows
	• Standardising approvals, notifications, and validations
	• Removing manual handoffs between teams
What this means for the business
	• Applications onboard faster and more predictably
	• Access changes are automated end-to-end
	• Less back-and-forth with central teams
	• Fewer delays caused by missing or incomplete information

3. Enabling self-service through one identity platform
What we are doing
	• Creating one identity entry point for business and technology teams
	• Power that experience using a consistent API layer
	• Support multiple channels from the same foundation (UI, system integrations, automation)
What this means for the business
	• One place to interact with identity
	• Consistent experience across tools and teams
	• Reduced reliance on tickets and manual requests
	• Identity becomes easier to consume and easier to trust

4. Improving resilience and reliability
What we are doing
	• Introducing monitoring and observability across identity workflows
	• Detecting failures early and recovering automatically
	• Applying SRE practices to identity services
What this means for the business
	• Fewer disruptions caused by identity failures
	• Faster resolution when issues occur
	• Confidence to automate more without increasing risk
	• Identity becomes predictable, not fragile

How this reduces cost for the business
This strategy directly reduces cost by:
	• Removing manual processing (70–80% reduction in manual access work)
	• Reducing rework caused by poor data quality
	• Eliminating duplicate integrations and bespoke solutions
	• Lowering operational effort to support audits and reviews
	• Reducing dependency on specialised skills and fragile customisations
The result is lower cost per application, lower cost per access decision, and lower cost to operate identity controls.

How this improves quality
	• Access decisions are based on real-time data
	• Reviews are accurate, targeted, and meaningful
	• Orphaned and inactive access is reduced
	• Controls reflect how applications actually behave
This leads to better security outcomes and stronger audit confidence, without increasing overhead.

How this accelerates delivery
	• Applications onboard faster
	• Identity changes propagate immediately
	• Business teams are less dependent on central queues
	• Identity becomes part of delivery pipelines, not a blocker
This allows the business to move faster without weakening controls.

The outcome
By executing this identity strategy, we are:
	• Reducing cost
	• Improving control quality
	• Increasing delivery speed
	• Creating a better experience for business teams
Most importantly, we are making identity work for the business, not the other way around.

One-sentence summary for executives
	“This strategy turns identity into a reliable, self-service platform that reduces cost, strengthens control, and enables the business to move faster with confidence.”

